markdown# AWS Load Balancer Controller Setup for EKS

## Prerequisites
- EKS Cluster running
- AWS CLI configured
- kubectl configured
- Helm installed
- eksctl installed

---

## Step 1 — Associate OIDC Provider
```bash
eksctl utils associate-iam-oidc-provider \
  --cluster devsecops \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --approve
```

---

## Step 2 — Create IAM Policy
```bash
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes-sigs/aws-load-balancer-controller/v2.7.1/docs/install/iam_policy.json

aws iam create-policy \
  --policy-name AWSLoadBalancerControllerIAMPolicy \
  --policy-document file://iam_policy.json
```

> **Note:** If you get `EntityAlreadyExists` error, skip this step and proceed to Step 3.

---

## Step 3 — Create IAM Service Account
```bash
eksctl create iamserviceaccount \
  --cluster=devsecops \
  --namespace=kube-system \
  --name=aws-load-balancer-controller \
  --role-name AmazonEKSLoadBalancerControllerRole \
  --attach-policy-arn=arn:aws:iam:::policy/AWSLoadBalancerControllerIAMPolicy \
  --region us-east-2 \
  --approve \
  --override-existing-serviceaccounts
```

---

## Step 4 — Install AWS Load Balancer Controller
```bash
helm repo add eks https://aws.github.io/eks-charts
helm repo update

helm install aws-load-balancer-controller eks/aws-load-balancer-controller \
  -n kube-system \
  --set clusterName=devsecops \
  --set serviceAccount.create=false \
  --set serviceAccount.name=aws-load-balancer-controller \
  --set region=us-east-2 \
  --set vpcId=$(aws eks describe-cluster \
      --name devsecops \
      --region us-east-2 \
      --query "cluster.resourcesVpcConfig.vpcId" \
      --output text)
```

### Verify Controller is Running
```bash
kubectl get pods -n kube-system \
  -l app.kubernetes.io/name=aws-load-balancer-controller

# Expected output:
# NAME                                            READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE
# aws-load-balancer-controller-xxx                1/1     Running   0          1m
# aws-load-balancer-controller-yyy                1/1     Running   0          1m
```

---

## Step 5 — Tag Public Subnets
```bash
# Get subnet IDs
aws ec2 describe-subnets \
  --filters "Name=vpc-id,Values=" \
  --query "Subnets[*].{ID:SubnetId,AZ:AvailabilityZone,Public:MapPublicIpOnLaunch}" \
  --output table

# Tag public subnets
aws ec2 create-tags \
  --resources    \
  --tags \
    Key=kubernetes.io/role/elb,Value=1 \
    Key=kubernetes.io/cluster/devsecops,Value=owned
```

---

## Step 6 — Create Namespace
```bash
kubectl create namespace three-tier
```

---

## Step 7 — Verify Services are Running
```bash
kubectl get svc -n three-tier

# Must show:
# NAME       TYPE        CLUSTER-IP   PORT(S)
# api        ClusterIP   x.x.x.x      3500/TCP
# frontend   ClusterIP   x.x.x.x      3000/TCP
```

